05000nam a22008775i 9789048522095DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014ne     fo  d z      eng d  a2016455675  a97890485220957 a10.1515/97890485220952doi  a(DE-B1597)517623  a(OCoLC)880148071  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL00aHD30.28b.W55 2014 4aHD30.28bW55 2014eb 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a3302221 aKupers, Roland, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Essence of Scenarios :bLearning from the Shell Experience /cAngela Wilkinson, Roland Kupers. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (185 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The "Gentle Art" -- tSources -- tI. A Unique Legacy -- tII. Shell Scenarios - A History, 1965-2013 -- tIII. The Essence of the Shell Art -- tIV. Looking Ahead -- tV. Conclusion -- tEpilogue: Scenario Team Leaders -- tAfterword -- tAppendix A - Timeline -- tAppendix B - Summary of Scenarios -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1965, Royal Dutch Shell started experimenting with a new approach to preparing for the future. This approach, called scenario planning, eschewed forecasting in favor of plausible alternative stories. By using stories, or "scenarios," Shell aimed to avoid the false assumption that the future would look much like the present-an assumption that marred most corporate planning at the time. The Essence of Scenarios offers unmatched insight into the company's innovative practice, which still has a huge influence on the way businesses, governments, and other organizations think about and plan for the future. In the course of their research, Angela Wilkinson and Roland Kupers interviewed almost every living veteran of the Shell scenario planning operation, along with many top Shell executives from later periods. Drawing on these interviews, the authors identify several principles that characterize the Shell process and explain how it has survived and thrived for so long. They also enumerate the qualities of successful Shell scenarios, which above all must be plausible stories with logical trajectories. Ultimately, Wilkinson and Kupers demonstrate the value of scenario planning as a sustained practice, rather than as a one-off exercise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aStrategic planning. 4aBLW. 4aEconomics. 4aPLS. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aManagement.  aScenario planning.  aStrategic planning.1 aHo, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilkinson, Angela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066278808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311070065740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048522095zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048522095423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048522095.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2002d2015  a978-3-11-070065-7  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_P